<p>As DIS returns to Germany for the first time since members Lauren Boyle, Solomon Chase, Marco Roso, and David Toro curated 2016’s hotly contested <a href="http://bb9.berlinbiennale.de/press/" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Berlin Biennale 9</a>, Boyle joins New Models to talk about the generation-defining project’s trajectory since its inception in the late-’00s, its recent film installation <em><a href="https://player.vimeo.com/video/791720988?h=ae402ea4ce" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Everything But The World</a> </em>(on view through Feb 26 at the <a href="https://www.schinkelpavillon.de/exhibition/everything-but-the-world" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer">Schinkel Pavillon</a> in Berlin), and its future vision. Along the way we discuss: subculture, pop culture, mass media, digital rot, and Gens X, Y, Z, and A.</p><figure><a href="https://substackcdn.com/image/fetch/f_auto,q_auto:good,fl_progressive:steep/https%3A%2F%2Fsubstack-post-media.s3.amazonaws.com%2Fpublic%2Fimages%2F909aeec7-82b3-4581-8cd1-baae211ef691_1000x1000.jpeg" rel="noopener noreferrer" target="_blank" referrerpolicy="no-referrer"><picture><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/vaYDdVf27o53oyBnrMnHFjZS-a- 424w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/fr-iAEGMln2gvPJv7imfWIHtreMZsaXFI-T5vNZU2Ss=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd184NDgsY19saW1pdCxmX3dlYnAscV9hdXRvOmdvb2QsZmxfcHJvZ3Jlc3NpdmU6c3RlZXAvaHR0cHMlM0ElMkYlMkZzdWJzdGFjay1wb3N0LW1lZGlhLnMzLmFtYXpvbmF3cy5jb20lMkZwdWJsaWMlMkZpbWFnZXMlMkY5MDlhZWVjNy04MmIzLTQ1ODEtOGNkMS1iYWFlMjExZWY2OTFfMTAwMHgxMDAwLmpwZWc= 848w, https://reader.miniflux. 1272w, https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/sh2UQCb9D4IQ- 1456w" sizes="100vw"/><img src="https://reader.miniflux.app/proxy/aGiGFveyk06dba_VZFgT6aRCxqN80aPJXwZlni-dtEU=/aHR0cHM6Ly9zdWJzdGFja2Nkbi5jb20vaW1hZ2UvZmV0Y2gvd18xNDU2LGNfbGltaXQsZl9hdXRvLHFfYXV0bzpn